tion. For example, using a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PartialRangeFrom"},{"type":"text","text":" range expression"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with an array accesses the subrange from the start of the range","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"expression until the end of the array."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let streets = [\"Adams\", \"Bryant\", \"Channing\", \"Douglas\", \"Evarts\"]","let streetsSlice = streets[2...]","print(streetsSlice)","\/\/ [\"Channing\", \"Douglas\", \"Evarts\"]"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The accessed slice uses the same indices for the same elements as the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"original collection uses. This example searches ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"streetsSlice"},{"text":" for one","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of the strings in the slice, and then uses that index in the original","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"array."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let index = streetsSlice.firstIndex(of: \"Evarts\")    \/\/ 4","print(streets[index!])","\/\/ \"Evarts\""],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Always use the slice’s "},{"code":"startIndex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" property instead of assuming that its"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"indices start at a particular value. Attempting to access an element by"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"using an index outside the bounds of the slice’s indices may result in a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"runtime error, even if that index is valid for the original collection."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["print(streetsSlice.startIndex)","\/\/ 2","print(streetsSlice[2])","\/\/ \"Channing\"","","print(streetsSlice[0])","\/\/ error: Index out of bounds"],"syntax":"s